SIMPLE: intension
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intension
<hw>In*ten"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>intensio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>intension</ets>. See <er>Intend</er>,
and cf. <er>Intention</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A straining, stretching, or bending; the state of
being strained; <as>as, the <ex>intension</ex> of a musical
string</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Increase of power or energy of any quality or thing;
intenseness; fervency.</def> <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sounds . . . likewise do rise and fall with the
<qex>intension</qex> or remission of the wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Logic & Metaph.)</fld> <def>The collective
attributes, qualities, or marks that make up a complex general notion;
the comprehension, content, or connotation; -- opposed to
<contr>extension</contr>, <contr>extent</contr>, or
<contr>sphere</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This law is, that the <qex>intension</qex> of our knowledge is in
the inverse ratio of its extension.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intensitive</ent>⟦br⟧
